      <div xml:id="NA250-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu putalvaṉoṭu pukka talaimakaṉ āṟṟāṉāyp pāṇaṟku uraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE who entered with [his] son said to the bard, being unable to bear it.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA250">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nakukam vārāy pāṇa pakuvā</l>
<l>            yaripey kiṇkiṇi yārppat teruviṟ</l>
<l>            ṟērnaṭai payiṟṟun tēmoḻip putalvaṉ</l>
<l>            pūnāṟu cevvāy citaitta cāntamoṭu</l>
<l>            kāmar neñcan turappa yāntaṉ </l>
<l>            muyaṅkal viruppoṭu kuṟukiṉē mākap</l>
<l>            piṟaivaṉap puṟṟa mācaṟu tirunuta</l>
<l>            ṉāṟiruṅ katuppiṉeṅ kātali vēṟuṇarntu</l>
<l>            verūumāṉ piṇaiyi ṉorīi</l>
<l>            yārai yōveṉ ṟikantuniṉ ṟatuvē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>We had to laugh<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nakukam</term> is a modal form without temporal impact, but the <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟukiṉēm āka</term> of the sub-clause makes clear that this is an account of was has already taken place.</note>, come, bard,</l>
<l rend="indent">at [her] standing aside, saying “who [are] you?”,</l>
<l rend="indent2">renouncing [us] as the doe the stag when it is frightened,</l>
<l rend="indent2">perceiving something else<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vēṟu-uṇarntu</term> can as well be taken into the simile (the doe perceiving something that frightens her) or into the main clause: SHE is looking at HIM as though she did not recognize him.</note>, our love with fragrant dark hair</l>
<l rend="indent3">[and] flawless brilliant forehead with crescent moon beauty,</l>
<l>when we came near with longing to embrace</l>
<l rend="indent">her, while a desirous heart was driving [us],</l>
<l>with the sandal paste [on our chest]<note place="foot">Syntactically, <term xml:lang="ta">cāntamoṭu</term> hangs on thin air (unless one wants to connect it with <term xml:lang="ta">neñcam</term>), and T.V.G.’s conjecture is that it is the sandal on HIS chest which is dissolved in the saliva of the child clinging to him.</note> spoiled by the flower-</l>
<l>smelling red mouth of [our] son with honey words,</l>
<l rend="indent2">repeating the gait of a chariot<note place="foot">That is, as T.V.G. plausibly explains, the child is learning to walk by pushing a toy chariot.</note> in the street,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while [his] slit-mouthed metal-filled anklets are tinkling.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
